						<summary>

						<p><hi rend="italic">Stone lying near the temple of Huḍēda Hanumān.</hi></p>						

						<p>Vāṇasatti-Arasa—(Undated).</p>						

						<p>This inscription, engraved in characters of about the <hi rend="bold">6-7th century A.D.,</hi> refers to <hi rend="bold">Vāṇasatti-arasa</hi> and his son governing <hi rend="bold">[Mū]ḷuṅgu[nda]</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Siri[gu*]ppe</hi> respectively and mentions <hi rend="bold">Kundasatti-arasa</hi> and <hi rend="bold">Vākka[ṭa]kaṇadē[vi].</hi> Vāṇasatti and Kundasatti appear to belong to the <hi rend="bold">Sēndraka</hi> family, the names of the princes of which usually end in <hi rend="bold">Satti</hi> (Skt. <hi rend="bold">Śakti</hi>). It is likely that Vāka[ṭ]akaṇadē[vi] belongs to the <hi rend="bold">Vākāṭaka</hi> family.</p>						

						<p>Vāṇasatti-arasa is not known from any other record.</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
